title: For Sale:  Hakim 8mm autoloading rifle
postcontent:
TRADE PENDING

Well, I bought two Hakims over the past two months, haven't had opportunity to shoot either yet, but I just got slammed by an unexpected bill so I'm going to put one of them up for sale.

I purchased this Hakim for $550.  Rifle is presented as functional in very good condition. Bore and gas tube look good. No problems feeding or extracting snap caps. This is a semi-automatic rifle that fires the 8mm mauser round from a detachable magazine, although stripper clips work well in these.

The Hakim comes standard with a 10 rd box magazine, although aftermarket 20 and 25 rd mags can be found on gunbroker. MG-13 magazines can be altered to fit the Hakim (tutorials available online).

Following caveats apply to all Hakims:

1. Never run Turkish ammunition through these as it is loaded way too hot. Yugo, Romy, and FN are fine.

2. American 8mm ammo isn't loaded hot enough to cycle a Hakim properly, although the gas flow can be adjusted to help with that.

3. Make certain the safety is switched ON if your fingers are going anywhere between the bolt and chamber, as that bolt can fly forward with considerable force.

This is a great rifle, but I have two and could use the extra cash.

Priced to sell at a hundred less than I paid for it at $450.  TRADE PENDING

Not really interested in trades, but might be interested in a 8mm Mauser + cash.  Sporterized Mausers are fine.  8mm only.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1944 Enfield long Branch No 4 Mk I*
postcontent: I'm selling my 1944 Long Branch rifle its a No 4 Mk I* It is a 303 cal. The wood is in very good condition and the blueing is good but there is some rust on the end of the barrel. The bore is in good condition it is a numbers matching gun.  Any questions please call REDACTED thank you. Very nice Long Branch markings – never seen such nice cartouches on the Know form, and the serial number is correct for mid to late 1944 production. The Brits got there hands on this too. The BNP stands for British Nitro Proof (Canada did not put proof marks on their weapons), and the other stamps on the Knox form are 2.222” (for the nominal length of a .303 cartridge) and the 18.5 tons per (square)” is the standard pressure for proofing (the rifles converted to the NATO 7.52 x 51 were later proofed to 19 tons). These are actually EXPORT stamps (for export from England), not import stamps

title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare Marlin Model 60 - 22" barrel, full length 18 round tube!
postcontent:
My 10 year old son shot a friends Marlin Model 60 and loved it.  So he purchased this one, however it is several inches longer than the one he fell in love with.  It also holds a total of 18 rounds instead of the standard 14 that he shot.  Consequently it is too heavy for him to hold up.

I did a bit of research and this is a bit of a rare model.  You usually had a pick of one or two of the features, but rare to find all of them together as there were not many factory made like this:

-  The feed tube is the full length of the barrel.
-  It holds 18 shots instead of the standard 14 (Prior to the New Jersey 15 rd max capacity law)
-  It has the additional bolt behind the trigger guard making it more sturdy and rigid that subsequent models.  
-  It has the "last shot hold open" that not all models have.
-  The longest barrel produced at 22" with an overall length of 41"
-  Microgroove Technology.

More info here:

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marlin_Model_60


This will be sold on a firearm bill of sale.  

Please text or call (for won seven) 379-seven ate ate ate.
